FOODBORNE ILLNESS - TANZANIA: (ZANZIBAR) SEA TURTLE MEAT, FATAL
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 29 Nov 2021
Source: BBC News [edited]
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-59458466


Seven people, including a 3-year-old, have died on Tanzania's Pemba island [Zanzibar] after eating poisonous turtle meat. 3 others are still in hospital.

The meat is a common delicacy among those living on Tanzania's islands and coastal areas but the authorities have now banned the consumption of turtles in the area. In rare cases, turtle meat can be toxic because of a type of food poisoning known as chelonitoxism.

Its exact cause is not known but it is thought to be linked to poisonous algae which the turtles eat, according to the Turtle Foundation charity.

At least 5 families on Pemba, which is part of the semi-autonomous Zanzibar islands, ate the turtle meat last Thursday, [25 Nov 2021], local police commander Juma Said Hamis told the BBC. The effects were first felt the next day and the 3-year-old was the first to die. 2 others died that night and then 4 more on Sunday, [28 Nov 2021]. A further 38 people were admitted to hospital, but most were discharged and the 3 who remain are said to be in a stable condition.

The poisoning can have the worst impact on children and older people, though healthier adults can also succumb, the Turtle Foundation says.

In March 2021 in Madagascar, 19 people, including 9 children, died after eating turtle meat, the AFP news agency reported at the time.

Cases have also been reported in Indonesia, Micronesia, and India's Indian Ocean islands.

[Byline: Maryam Abdalla]

